passages.text: Urban Outfitters, Inc.

URBN reported 2Q25 that beat on sales, GM, EPS, and consolidated comps \((+5.6\%)\) vs. cons. \(+5.0\%\) ). UO brand comps accelerated sequentially to \(+4.2\%\) (vs. cons. \(+2.1\%\) ). The company now expects a 75bps headwind to GM in 2H25 due to tariffs but despite that it believes it can expand FY25 GM by \(+100\) bps.

When all 5 Brands Start Working...That's One Way to Offset Tariff Impact. All five of URBN's brands, Anthropologie, Free People, Urban Outfitters, Free People Movement, and Nudly, are all growing sales and expanding margins. Despite tariff headwinds, fundamental outperformance is certainly one way - and the best way - to offset the rising cost of tariffs. URBN reported 2Q25 that beat on sales, GM, and EPS, and consolidated comps \((+5.6\%)\) vs. cons. \(+5.0\%\) ). UO brand comps accelerated sequentially to \(+4.2\%\) (vs. cons. \(+2.1\%\) ). The company now expects a 75bps headwind to GM in 2H25 due to tariffs but despite that, it believes it can expand FY25 GM by \(+100\) bps. We are impressed with the material ability at URBN to offset the impact of tariffs driven by multiple levers including: 1) regular price selling and less markdowns, 2) higher sales mix of own- brands, 3) adjusting mode of transportation from air to ocean, 4) shifting its sourcing mix, and 5) potentially and strategically "gently" raising prices only if necessary in the future. During the quarter we saw broad- based strength across all brands, with each posting positive comps and operating income improvement. The company expects this momentum to continue as management guided for 3Q25 sales to grow \(+\) HSD driven by \(+\) MSD comps for all brands. We previewed the quarter and highlighted the improvement observed in our promo tracker for 2Q25 at the UO brand (Figure 8) and its reduction in promos, which management acknowledged was a large driver of the \(+113\) bps increase to GM due to overall lower markdowns. With improving product margins driven by strong regular price selling and a reduction in markdowns combined with positive comps, we see signs that the turn is here. We remain Overweight shares of URBN based on: 1) our expectation that the company is embarking on a multiyear journey to right the UO brand with mounting, and convincing, evidence of margin and sales improvement in 2Q25; 2) ongoing momentum at Free People and Anthropologie; 3) positive- to- accelerating regular price selling, both in the digital and store channels; and 4) significant growth at Nudly with a market dominant position and FP Movement. In reaction on 8/27/25, in the aftermarket URBN shares traded \(- 6.4\%\) versus S&P 500 flat.

FY25 GM by \(+100\) bps. Because they still use significant air, unlike retailers with slower turning inventory, URBn will see the impact of both the 8/7/25 tariffs and 8/25/25 increase to \(50\%\) India tariff on 4Q25 performance. Even so, 4Q25 GM is expected to be up 75 to 100 bps. URBn continues to work on mitigation strategies to offset increased costs by: 1) negotiating better terms with vendors; 2) diversifying countries of origin; 3) changing the mode of transportation from air to ocean; and 4) strategically adjusting pricing.

Quarter in review. 2Q25 adj. EPS of \(1.58\) beat vs. consensus of \(1.48\) , driven by higher sales and a GM beat, partially offset by OpEx as a \(\%\) of sales deleverage. Sales of \(1.51\) bn came in ahead versus consensus of \(1.48\) bn as sales at the UO brand and Free People came in ahead of consensus, while Anthro was in- line. Consolidated comps of \(+5.6\%\) came in ahead (vs. cons. \(+5.0\%\) ), with Free People (comp sales \(+6.7\%\) ), Anthro \((+5.7\%)\) , and Urban Outfitters \((+4.2\%)\) . GM of \(37.6\%\) beat (vs. cons. of \(37.4\%\) ), primarily driven by lower markdowns, as well as occupancy leverage. OpEx as a \(\%\) of sales of \(26.0\%\) missed consensus of \(25.7\%\) , primarily driven by higher marketing expenses. Additionally, guidance for 3Q25 was provided with total company sales growth of \(+HSD\) (vs. cons. \(+7.6\%\) ), driven by \(+MSD\) retail segment comp sales (vs. cons. \(+4.5\%\) ), attributable to \(+MSD\) comps at Anthro, FP, and UO, and mid double- digit growth at Nuuly; GM expected to be flat (vs. cons. \(+30\) bps); SG&A as a \(\%\) of sales deleverage (vs. cons. \(+20\) bps) due to increased marketing expenses; and a tax rate of \(23.7\%\) . For 4Q25 the company expects GM to expand \(+75\) bps to \(+100\) bps (vs. cons. \(+30\) bps) and SG&A as a \(\%\) of sales leverage (vs. cons. flat). Additionally for FY25, management raised its GM guide to \(+100\) bps (vs. prior \(+50\) bps to \(+100\) bps and vs. cons. \(+90\) bps) and expects a tax rate of \(23.0\%\) .

Inventory. Based on our proprietary inventory analysis, URBn has posted four consecutive quarters of negative sales- to- inventory growth. In FY2Q25 the Inventory Management Spread ("IM Spread") was (360) basis points and worsened from (307) basis points in the prior quarter. URBn's Gross Margin Return on Inventory ("GMROI") has improved for three consecutive quarters, and its Operating Margin Return on Inventory ("OMROI") has improved for ten consecutive quarters.

Raising EPS estimates; maintaining PT of \(89\) . Our FY25, FY26, and FY27 EPS estimates are \(5.26\) , \(5.70\) , and \(5.96\) (from \(5.08\) , \(5.54\) , and \(5.94\) ), respectively, driven by higher sales and an increase in our gross profit assumptions. Our PT is \(89\) (unchanged), based on an NTM P/E multiple of \(15x\) (from \(16x\) ) applied to our CY27 adj. EPS estimate of \(5.96\) (from CY26 adj. EPS estimate of \(5.54\) ). We roll forward our PT, which is now based on our CY27 EPS estimate vs. our prior CY26 estimate.

From a fundamental perspective, we use our proprietary PRISM cycle as a leading indicator of a potential sales inflection (i.e., either from positive to negative or negative to positive). Our PRISM Curve attempts to look for fundamental changes in the business model of a company, driven by proactive management decisions to stabilize margins (e.g., purge inventory, cut costs, share best practices, invest in product and brand). Figure 2 and Figure 3 below depict our model graphically and identify where we would theoretically expect to see sales and margin changes along the business model curve.

During the HUNT Phase, management's strategy is on the offense. They are in "HUNT" mode and are in control of taking market share. Management is focused on driving company- specific strategies forward, building on their own brand equity and positioning, rather than focusing primarily on competitors or the environment around them. At this point, retailers are usually beating sales and margin expectations and may begin to grow earnings faster than total sales. Investors would want to hold and accumulate shares of a company in Region C in Figure 3, the area of maximum potential stock appreciation. This phase may take place over multiple years as the company enters its sweet spot.

Tariff Exposure Update. The company anticipates a 75bps headwind to GM in 2H25 due to tariffs specifically on its own brand product (this does not include market brands), which includes the revised \(50\%\) India tariff. Despite the headwind, management believes it can expand FY25 GM by \(+100\) bps. Because they still use significant air, unlike retailers with slower turning inventory, URBn will see the impact of both the 8/7/25 tariffs and 8/25/25 increase to \(50\%\) India tariff on 4Q25 performance. Even so, 4Q25 GM is expected to be up 75 to 100 bps. URBn continues to work on mitigation strategies to offset increased costs by: 1) negotiating better terms with vendors; 2) diversifying countries of origin; 3) changing the mode of transportation from air to ocean; and 4) strategically adjusting pricing.

Prior tariff commentary. URBn commented that they expect a minimal impact from tariffs and will work to offset increased cost by: 1) shift countries of sourcing; 2) shift mode of transportation from air to boat when appropriate; and 3) as a last resort pass through very strategic and targeting price increases only if necessary. The primary sourcing countries are India, Vietnam, and Turkey and no country represents more than \(25\%\) sourcing. China sourcing is less than \(5\%\) .

Barclays Tariff "QuikCalc" Model assumptions. We have updated our Tariff "QuikCalc" model analysis, which now assumes global tariff assumptions effective 8/7/25. Our prior tariff analysis had assumed \(30\%\) China and \(10\%\) Rest of World (excluding Mexico and Canada). Additionally, we adjust our assumptions for non- product COS to \(28\%\) (was \(20\%\) ), implying low- to- mid \(60\%\) merchandise margins across URBn. We also lower the \(5\%\) sourced outside of the US to \(50\%\) (was \(100\%\) ) as the company only incurs direct own- brand tariff related costs (not including market brand tariff exposure). Note our estimate of Tariff on Goods Imported to the US is a gross unmitigated amount for a full year, and we calculate the price increase necessary to mitigate full tariff cost (absent other mitigation strategies). Our updated tariff calculator under 8/7/25 effective rates, suggests that for URBn, total average unit cost could increase by \(11.4\%\) with pass- through to the U.S. market if only increasing prices to fully offset costs by \(4.6\%\) (see Figure 11).
